photos.title: Die Trying

description._content:
Meet Chaos 1 and Chaos 2. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Hey guys.

Sorry I haven't posted in forever. I've been really busy with life - school, friends, family, photography, music, business, SAT.. the list goes on. A lot's happened in the past few months. 

I hope these figures begin to compensate for my absence. My apologies for the awful photo. I've missed you guys. I promise I'll do my best do be more active, and post more material. 

And hey, I definitely need funds for minifig parts, so just ask and I'll tag you in a sale/trade photo that'll be up soon. Or FM me, that works too. 

In addition, all of the figures I post and have posted (except for a few) are for sale. If I'm ever going to keep on doing this, I need money for new projects. Would you guys be interested in me doing figure commissions, or managing a bricklink store? 

Thanks for your patience with me everyone. 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

photos.title: Wild Goose Island

description._content:
......one of Glacier National Park’s most photographed spots.

Island Folk Tale;

Wild Goose Island is in the middle of St. Mary Lake. A long time ago, two native tribes resided on opposite sides of St. Mary’s. Even though they seldom fought, they had no interaction. One day, a strikingly handsome warrior from one tribe noticed a beautiful woman on the other swimming toward the island. He couldn’t resist her beauty immediately swam to meet her on the island. The two met, clicked instantly, spoke for hours, and became engaged. They promised to meet again tomorrow morning on the island and each swam home.
Upon reaching their tribal shores, they realized they had created a massive problem. Each tribe’s elders demanded that the engagement be broken off.
Well, the two lovers didn’t agree and met each other the next morning on the island. After a quick discussion, they decided to run away and find their own land to marry and live.
When the tribal elders found out, they sent war parties to retreive their members and were determined to bring them home, no matter wha the cost.
Thankfully, the Great Spirit had kept its eyes on the two lovers. Taking pity on them, he transformed them into geese so they could fly away and be together forever. When the tribal warriors arrived on the island, all they found were two geese, tenderly rubbing necks. They flew away and never returned.
From then on, the small island in the center of St. Mary’s Lake in Glacier National Park was known as Wild Goose Island.

photos.title: wildfire

description._content:
I've had this picture tucked away in my "In Progress" folder for a year now, at least. I'm not sure why I never edited it before, or why I felt compelled to now, but somehow it spoke to me and my passion was renewed. 


This picture holds many meanings and inspirations...Ideas spread like wildfire and it is up to us to make sure the right ones catch on. Red - bold and striking - a favorite color of mine to use in an image because of what it symbolizes: blood, life, death, strength and weakness all in one.


I was so excited by this landscape because I could envision all of the lines that the final image would hold - the mountains cutting across one another, and a piece of red fabric doing the same. I love repetition in an image because so often it points to deeper meanings.


Have an inspired week ahead!

photos.title: Blue Night ✵ Nuit bleue

description._content: Take a peak in the lightroom: www.flickr.com/photos/chizuka/10656367604/lightbox/ The theme for week 44 of the 52 in 2013 group is is Long Exposure Le défi thématique pour la 44e semaine du groupe 52 in 2013 est Longue exposition. This is a picture of Ottawa (on the left) and Gatineau (on the other side of the river) taken from the Rideau Falls (61 sec ƒ/20 ISO 250 10 mm) It was 3º Celsius (37 º F) last night when I went out to take pictures for this week’s theme. It was cold and windy. As I set up my tripod by the waterfall viewpoint, feeling a little scared because I was alone in the dark, I was wondering why I was doing this. Needless to say, my commitment to the group was dwindling as my fingers froze and the cold wind was going right through me. I was standing there, counting the seconds for each shot (between 45 and 120 seconds) and I was getting colder by the minute, mostly because I was not moving. I had decided to wear my winter coat, hoping it would keep me warm, but it did not. It takes the body a few weeks to acclimatize to the cold weather. The notion of cold is relative. Right now, 3º Celsius feels really cold, but a month or so from now, I’ll be out in -20 C and probably won’t feel much colder than I did last night. The funny thing is that in early March when the temperature goes up to 5º Celsius, we say that it is warm and we start taking layers of clothes off…, but not now, not in early November. And that's the way it is in Eastern Canada!!!

photos.title: the cattle egret's spring attire (Explore, 3/11/2013)

description._content: Cattle Egret Scientific Name: Ardea ibis Description: A relatively small snowy-white egret, the Cattle Egret is distinguished during breeding season by its orange crown, neck and breast, with similarly tinted long loose neck plumes. The long sharp, slightly down-curved bill is yellow to pinkish yellow, but becomes bright red during breeding season. The legs are normally grey-green out of breeding season, turning bright red or orange-brown during breeding. It is a gregarious species and is most commonly seen foraging with grazing stock and in wetland areas. Similar species: Outside breeding season, The Cattle Egret may be confused with other white egrets such as the Intermediate Egret, A. intermedia, which has a longer neck and is less stocky or the Little Egret, A garzetta, which always has a very slender black bill and is much slimmer in profile. The Great Egret, A. alba, is much larger, with a longer neck and legs and a slimmer body. In breeding season, the orange plumage of the Cattle Egret makes it unmistakable. Distribution: Originally found in Africa, Europe and Asia, the Cattle Egret is now found on nearly every continent, with birds in Australia originating from Asia. In Australia it is most widespread and common in north-eastern Western Australia across the Top End, Northern Territory, and in south-eastern Australia from Bundaberg, Queensland to Port Augusta, South Australia, including Tasmania. Habitat: The Cattle Egret is found in grasslands, woodlands and wetlands, and is not common in arid areas. It also uses pastures and croplands, especially where drainage is poor. Will also forage at garbage dumps, and is often seen with cattle and other stock. Minimum Size: 48cm Maximum Size: 53cm Average size: 50cm Breeding season: October to March Clutch Size: 2 to 7, usually 3 Incubation: 24 days Nestling Period: 42 days (Source: www.birdsinbackyards.net ) __________________________________________ © All rights reserved. photos.title: Starlings

description._content: © 2013 Alan Mackenzie. www.alanmackenziephotography.com It's that time of year again, when starlings form murmurations over Brighton Pier. An estimated two or three thousand birds gathered on Saturday 2nd November 2013. This will inevitably increase over the coming weeks. I have made it my intention to be present on a very regular basis, provided the sun is visible. Sunshine and showers or clear skies is best. Hazy mid-to-high level cloud results in an unattractive blown out solar disk. Photographing starling murmurations is extremely difficult, even with a Canon 1-series body and 300mm f/2.8 lens. Most shots taken are rejected. Some of my best photos from last winter were taken within seconds of each other. It all depends on a number of factors occurring at the right time, hence the need to be at the pier at every available opportunity. On a final note, you may recall that a starling photo of mine from last year was short-listed in a competition run by the Sussex Wildlife Trust. Here are the winners... www.sussexwildlifetrust.org.uk/blog/2013/10/fox-on-top/

photos.title: Waschbär

description._content:
Zoom Erlebniswelt Gelsenkirchen / Oktober 2013

Die Waschbären (Procyon) sind eine Gattung der Kleinbären (Procyonidae). Von den drei Arten der Gattung ist der auch in Europa als Neozoon eingebürgerte (Nordamerikanische) Waschbär der bekannteste. Waschbären sind entgegen früheren Behauptungen keine Einzelgänger, sondern haben ein komplexes Sozialverhalten. Manchmal leben Weibchen in kleinen Gruppen, auch junge Männchen teilen sich Territorien, die Streifgebiete können sich überschneiden. Sie sind vorwiegend dämmerungs- oder nachtaktiv und schlafen tagsüber in Baumhöhlen oder anderen Unterschlupfen. Sie sind Allesfresser, die sowohl pflanzliche Nahrung als auch Wirbellose und kleine Wirbeltiere zu sich nehmen.

photos.title: Atomium Brussels, various aspects (Explored #122 on 03-11-2013)

description._content: Unmistakable symbol of Brussels and Belgium and unique feat in the history of architecture: the Atomium is today the most popular attraction in the capital of Europe. Built for the 1958 World Exhibition, the Atomium is shaped on the model of an elementary iron crystal enlarged 165 billion times. Beyond surreal walks through tubes and the 9 spheres, the Atomium houses a permanent exhibition about its history as well temporary exhibitions for a broad public (sciences, design, society).The upper sphere offers unique and spectacular views across the city skyline. (To be posted soon) At night, 2970 lights offer a fairy dimension to the 102m high building. The panoramic restaurant is daily open until 11pm. All my images are protected under international authors copyright laws and may not be downloaded, reproduced, copied, transmitted or manipulated without my written explicit permission. photos.title: Rouge the Cross House

description._content:
Red Mountain Ash berries against the blue sky with the Rouge restaurant, (heritage A.E.Cross house)
 This historic house is now a restaurant and I celebrated my 50th birthday here a while ago!

From the restaurant's website:
The House

Built in 1891, and the former home of A.E. Cross, one of The Big Four, The Cross House is a designated Calgary Municipal and Province of Alberta Heritage site. The house is nested on the banks of The Bow River in the beautiful and historic community of Inglewood. We are only 5 minutes from downtown Calgary, and offer ample free parking.
The A.E. Cross House was built in 1891 and acquired by Cross eight years later. The home is one of Calgary's oldest residences and manifests several unusual architectural elements typical of the time. These include the hip roof, sandstone foundation, "widow's walk" balustrade, and gingerbread trim. Such embellishments reflect the sensibilities of Calgary's wealthier citizens in the late Victorian period. The building remains a significant local landmark in the city's historic "Old Town" area.

photos.title: 272 - Bóveda - Mezquita Cristo de la Luz (Toledo) - Spain.

description._content:
Disfrutemos de esta bóveda, joya del arte musulmán, siendo una de las nueve bóvedas existentes, todas ellas diferentes en la mezquita construida en el año 999 – 1000, que pertenece a la época califal.
Esta mezquita pasó a ser la ermita del Cristo de la Luz (Toledo) – Spain, siendo este edificio milenario un ejemplar único en el arte de Al-Andalus.
---------------------------------------------------------------
Let us enjoy this vault, jewel of Muslim art, one of the nine existing vaults, all different in the mosque built in the year 999 - 1000, which belongs to during the Caliphate.
This mosque became the Chapel of Christ the Light (Toledo) - Spain, and this millennial building a single original in the art of Al-Andalus.

photos.title: The Wendelstein Rack Railway

description._content:
My son wanted me to upload this one, too. Actually, I hoped, that one or the other of his pictures would get an explore :-)) That would have made his day. And I think, the picture with the people standing in front of the cloudy valley is the best, that we have taken. Well... explore and I have a different taste.

The Wendelstein Rack Railway[1] (German: Wendelsteinbahn), sometimes just referred to as the Wendelstein Railway, is an electrically-driven metre gauge rack railway (with several adhesion sections) that runs up the Wendelstein in the Upper Bavarian Limestone Alps. Together with the Wendelstein Cable Car (Wendelstein-Seilbahn) it is operated by the Wendelsteinbahn GmbH. The mountain railway climbs through a total height of 1,217.27 metres (3,993.7 feet). The Wendelstein Railway is one of only four working rack railways in Germany, the others being the Bavarian Zugspitze Railway, the Drachenfels Railway and the Stuttgart Rack Railway.

photos.title: The Quilt

description._content:
The leaves had a wonderful frolic.
They danced to the wind's loud song.
They whirled, and they floated, and scampered.
They circled and flew along.

The moon saw the little leaves dancing.
Each looked like a small brown bird.
The man in the moon smiled and listened.
And this is the song he heard.

The North Wind is calling, is calling,
And we must whirl round and round,
And then, when our dancing is ended,
We'll make a warm quilt for the ground.

Anonymous

description._content: We temporarily interrupt the recent cavalcade of darkish and somewhat dreary photos for some momentary enlightenment. Just as I was beginning to comment on the notable dearth of nice sunrises lately, the telltale signs of a potentially special display caught my attention this morning and sent me scrambling to the shore so that I might avoid the intervening trees, familiar to many of you from previous shots from the deck.  While these hints can sometimes be a tease, such was not the case on this Sunday, unfolding dramatically for quickly fleeting but memorable moments. [SOOC]
